<div id="review_3071349782" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3071349782" />
    <a title="Anita Fajita Pita" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/42009094-anita-fajita-pita"><img alt="Anita Fajita Pita" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1556726615p2/42009094.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3071349782?book_show_action=true">Jul 19, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Anita Fajita Pita" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Anita Fajita Pita" href="/user/show/42009094-anita-fajita-pita">Anita Fajita Pita</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/42009094-anita-fajita-pita?shelf=read-black-women-2021">read-black-women-2021</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/42009094-anita-fajita-pita?shelf=2021">2021</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/42009094-anita-fajita-pita?shelf=nonfic-educate-myshelf">nonfic-educate-myshelf</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3071349782" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2025209065873499346">A very important read for anyone looking to further their own knowledge on American history, and especially to educate ones self on the dark medical history and scientific progress built on the lives of African Americans. Very relevant and important.<br/><br/>I also want to add that this is a heavy read because of the material, but it isn&apos;t necessarily a morbid book. Simply reading the title tells you that this is a dark history, a.n unending parade of atrocities framed in a book titled &apos;Medical Apartheid</span>
  <span id="freeText2025209065873499346" style="display:none">A very important read for anyone looking to further their own knowledge on American history, and especially to educate ones self on the dark medical history and scientific progress built on the lives of African Americans. Very relevant and important.<br /><br />I also want to add that this is a heavy read because of the material, but it isn't necessarily a morbid book. Simply reading the title tells you that this is a dark history, a.n unending parade of atrocities framed in a book titled 'Medical Apartheid.' It can't be anything other than heavy. <br /><br />It also toes the line between things you already 'know' with all the research and facts about actual events, so while it might at times seem like you already knew that, did you really <i>actually</i> know the facts about, say, the Tuskegee experiments, or the astoundingly higher numbers of Black bodies stolen and sold to medical schools compared to white bodies - sometimes not even actually dead bodies. </span>
  <a data-text-id="2025209065873499346" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


